 Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":6,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705187,"age":115,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Gilbert d'Oilly was born in 1100, in England. She had at least 3 sons with Gilbert d'Oilly the Younger."},"et":{"1100–":"1100–Surnud","1096–1149":"1096–1149","1125–Male":"1125–Surnud","1138–1189":"1138–1189","1142–1192":"1142–1192","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","1106":"1106","1138":"1138","1215":"1215","1149":"1149","1125":"1125","1189":"1189","1100":"1100","um 1125":"umbes 1125","1142":"1142","1096":"1096","1192":"1192","Aston, Oxfordshire, England":"Aston, Oxfordshire, England","England":"England","Hook Norton, Oxfordshire, England":"Hook Norton, Oxfordshire, England"},"fi":{"1100–":"1100–Kuollut","1096–1149":"1096–1149","1125–Male":"1125–Kuollut","1138–1189":"1138–1189","1142–1192":"1142–1192","1100–Female":"1100–Kuollut","1106":"1106","1138":"1138","1215":"1